The Met=E2=80=99s new show of echt German romanticist Caspar David Friedric=
h, whom
Hitler co-opted for fascist appeal, raises some interesting questions about=
 our cultural moment. Is Friedrich, the progenitor of a style now more fami=
liar in comic books than art history books, worth taking seriously?

Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F11%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Why is the Met=E2=80=99s new show, Caspar David Friedrich: The Soul of
Nature=E2=80=94a detailed retrospective of an artist that most Americans ar=
e only familiar with due to a popular meme=E2=80=94getting so much attentio=
n? I thought about this question last week as I stood on the steps of the M=
et early one morning, in a freezing drizzle, listening to a clutch of Germa=
n art dignitaries chatter away brightly as we waited for the doors to open.=
 There are probably two answers.

First, with 88 paintings and drawings, the Met=E2=80=99s current show of
Friedrich=E2=80=99s work=E2=80=94its third in 35 years=E2=80=94will be the =
largest, and =E2=80=9Cvery first major retrospective in the United States o=
f Germany=E2=80=99s most beloved painter,=E2=80=9D as the Met=E2=80=99s dir=
ector, Max Hollein, described it. The show features works on loan from thre=
e German museums=E2=80=94including the main draw, Friedrich=E2=80=99s Wande=
rer above the Sea of Fog, the familiar image of a windswept early 19th cent=
ury figure perched on a rocky outcropping, surveying a vista filled with sc=
uds of fog that could
easily be mistaken for a tempestuous sea. The show is certainly an event wo=
rthy of the 250th anniversary of the artist=E2=80=99s birth last year.

Caspar David Friedrich, Wanderer above the Sea of Fog (ca. 1817)

Caspar David Friedrich, Wanderer above the Sea of
Fog (ca. 1817)

A quarter-millennium in, Friedrich is also having a moment in meme
culture. =E2=80=9CWanderer above the Sea of Fog has begun to turn up in Ame=
rican popular imagery in ways that are highly specific to our national dial=
ogue,=E2=80=9D the Met=E2=80=99s Alison Hokanson, one of the show=E2=80=99s=
 curators, wrote in her excellent catalog essay tracing the serpentine and =
complicated legacy of Friedrich in the United States. =E2=80=9CReworked in =
explicitly political contexts, the picture=E2=80=99s various appropriations=
 run the gamut from assertions of white nationalism to
the promotion of liberal environmental and economic programs.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Indeed, though relatively few of Friedrich=E2=80=99s works are present in t=
he U.S., American museums own all five of the Wanderer paintings=E2=80=94wh=
ich the Met has gathered together for the first time. During the preview, h=
eavily attended by museum professionals, I could see that the show was inst=
itutionally driven: Representatives of the German and
American museums seemed quite chuffed to see their hard work come together.=
 I also got a sense I can=E2=80=99t fully explain that this kind of show wo=
uld be quite popular with a segment of the donor class ( https://puck.news/=
wall-street-is-still-aboard-the-trump-train/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%282%2F11%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F1=
1%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c=
60617da42abd12a ). Art, like politics, has a small but vital constituency t=
hat often determines what takes place more than the public, itself.=C2=A0

That said, this is
not a case of elite mandarins mounting a show of little interest to the ple=
bs. Friedrich=E2=80=99s contemplative wanderer atop his rocky promontory ha=
s been grafted into numerous alternative contexts, from futuristic panorama=
s to apocalyptic hellscapes to riffs on everything from Star Wars to manga.=
 There=E2=80=99s clearly something about German romanticism that resonates =
two centuries later. Like the romantics, we live in an era of overwhelming =
technological and political upheaval, and often want to
believe that there is something more that animates our spirits. And, just a=
s in Friedrich=E2=80=99s day, there are overtly political purposes to this =
distraction from our rational abilities.=C2=A0

The Wanderer
------------

Friedrich was born in the Baltic seaport of Greifswald, which is now in
Germany but was then part of Sweden. (At the time, the Baltic was effective=
ly a Swedish lake.) Raised a strict Lutheran, he migrated to Copenhagen to =
begin a classical artist=E2=80=99s training in drawing body parts from plas=
ter casts before graduating to drawing figures from life. In Copenhagen, Fr=
iedrich seems to have developed a love of drawing landscapes, sketching out=
side instead of in a studio. But he also dropped out of his studies halfway=
 through and moved to Dresden, the far side of
not-yet-unified Germany, which was then a cosmopolitan center of commerce a=
nd art near the border of what=E2=80=99s now the Czech Republic.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

There, Friedrich found a synthesis of his own religious ideas, a growing Ge=
rman nationalism under Napoleonic French occupation, and a stripped-down ae=
sthetic of landscape imagery. He first worked all this out in sparse drawin=
gs and etchings often overlaid with a sepia
wash that gives them a haunting quality. Those works on paper gave Friedric=
h his first critical success, which allowed him to launch himself as a pain=
ter.=C2=A0

And that=E2=80=99s where the Met=E2=80=99s show begins to take off. You can=
 chart the ideas that culminate in the Wanderer, the apotheosis of German r=
omanticism, or you can simply indulge in the moody, luminous imagery of clo=
ud studies, seascapes, and reflective depictions of the r=C3=BCckenfigur, a=
 figure seen
from behind who beckons the viewer to contemplate the image before both.

Caspar David Friedrich, Woman before the Rising or Setting Sun (ca. 1818)

Caspar David Friedrich, Woman before the Rising or Setting
Sun (ca. 1818)

There=E2=80=99s no denying that Friedrich is an artist whose work is pleasi=
ng to
behold and straightforward in its emotional pull. (Though you will benefit =
from reading the excellent catalogue if you really want to understand the f=
ormal innovations that he employed and how those intersect with Napoleonic-=
era political and religious ideas.) But, yes, 200 years on, the images can =
seem tritely familiar from popular culture imagery, comic book dramatic eff=
ects, or even less subtle art. Indeed, given the way Friedrich=E2=80=99s in=
novations resonate through kitsch, it=E2=80=99s a surprise that
the Met hasn=E2=80=99t leaned further in that direction as a way to make th=
e show more obviously relevant.

I get that such an approach would trivialize Friedrich=E2=80=99s importance=
 as an artist. And I should acknowledge that there=E2=80=99s a very good ca=
talogue essay on the Wanderer in popular culture. But I also know that ther=
e=E2=80=99s something on the other side of the intellectual and cultural sp=
ectrum that isn=E2=80=99t being addressed here. Elements of Friedrich=E2=80=
=99s
visual innovations were meant to express his own historically and religious=
ly specific longing to exalt individual experience over cold rationalism, a=
nd also a desire to evoke a nationalistic identity=E2=80=94themes that late=
r became central to German fascism, and which endeared him to Hitler=E2=80=
=94who, you may recall, originally aspired to be an artist before becoming =
a genocidal totalitarian. We, too, are living through a nationalist moment,=
 and one where the exaltation of the irrational in the name of
individual empowerment and redemption has become a daily occurrence. Friedr=
ich isn=E2=80=99t responsible for this, but it is spooky that we should hav=
e a detailed and extensive show of his work open just as the most negative =
aspects of romanticism are playing out in our own politics.=C2=A0

Here it is important to note, as the exhibition does so very well, that Fri=
edrich=E2=80=99s own fame and importance was brief. Friedrich painted the f=
irst Wanderer in 1817, it is believed,
but by 1825 he had been denied the chair of landscape painting at the Dresd=
en academy=E2=80=94a sinecure he would have coveted. His style would subseq=
uently be eclipsed by that of the Dusseldorf Academy, which had a more dire=
ct influence on American landscape painting later in the century. Much of F=
riedrich=E2=80=99s work, which is now displayed in Germany or Russia, was f=
orgotten and had to be rediscovered at various times, for purposes it=E2=80=
=99s doubtful that Friedrich would have supported. All of which is to say
that the appeal of this kind of romanticism is recurring, but not long-live=
d. Or, maybe I should say, let=E2=80=99s hope it=E2=80=99s not long-lived t=
his time.

