50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">A quarter-millennium in, Friedrich is also having a moment i=
n meme
culture. =E2=80=9C<em>Wanderer above the Sea of Fog</em> has begun to turn =
up in American popular imagery in ways that are highly specific to our nati=
onal dialogue,=E2=80=9D the Met=E2=80=99s <strong>Alison Hokanson</strong>,=
 one of the show=E2=80=99s curators, wrote in her excellent catalog essay t=
racing the serpentine and complicated legacy of Friedrich in the United Sta=
tes. =E2=80=9CReworked in explicitly political contexts, the picture=E2=80=
=99s various appropriations run the gamut from assertions of white national=
ism to
the promotion of liberal environmental and economic programs.=E2=80=9D</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">Indeed, though relatively few of Friedrich=E2=80=99s works =
are present in the U.S., American museums own all five of the <em>Wanderer<=
/em> paintings=E2=80=94which the Met has gathered together for the first ti=
me. During the preview, heavily attended by museum professionals, I could s=
ee that the show was institutionally driven: Representatives of the German =
and
American museums seemed quite chuffed to see their hard work come together.=
 I also got a sense I can=E2=80=99t fully explain that this kind of show wo=
uld be quite popular with a <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFp=
bF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVOTVYZDVkX3pIcm45VC03Y193az0iLCJocmVmIjo=
iaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3Mvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtaXMtc3RpbGwtYWJvYXJkLXRoZS10cnVtcC=
