><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">There=E2=80=99s no denying that Friedrich is an artist whose=
 work is pleasing to
behold and straightforward in its emotional pull. (Though you will benefit =
from reading the excellent catalogue if you really want to understand the f=
ormal innovations that he employed and how those intersect with Napoleonic-=
era political and religious ideas.) But, yes, 200 years on, the images can =
seem tritely familiar from popular culture imagery, comic book dramatic eff=
ects, or even less subtle art. Indeed, given the way Friedrich=E2=80=99s in=
novations resonate through kitsch, it=E2=80=99s a surprise that
the Met hasn=E2=80=99t leaned further in that direction as a way to make th=
e show more obviously relevant.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">I get that such an approach would trivialize Friedrich=E2=80=99s=
 importance as an artist. And I should acknowledge that there=E2=80=99s a v=
ery good catalogue essay on the <em>Wanderer</em> in popular culture. But I=
 also know that there=E2=80=99s something on the other side of the intellec=
tual and cultural spectrum that isn=E2=80=99t being addressed here. Element=
s of Friedrich=E2=80=99s
visual innovations were meant to express his own historically and religious=
ly specific longing to exalt individual experience over cold rationalism, a=
nd also a desire to evoke a nationalistic identity=E2=80=94themes that late=
r became central to German fascism, and which endeared him to Hitler=E2=80=
=94who, you may recall, originally aspired to be an artist before becoming =
a genocidal totalitarian. We, too, are living through a nationalist moment,=
 and one where the exaltation of the irrational in the name of
individual empowerment and redemption has become a daily occurrence. Friedr=
ich isn=E2=80=99t responsible for this, but it is spooky that we should hav=
e a detailed and extensive show of his work open just as the most negative =
aspects of romanticism are playing out in our own politics.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Here it is important to note, as the exhibition does =
so very well, that Friedrich=E2=80=99s own fame and importance was brief. F=
riedrich painted the first <em>Wanderer</em> in 1817, it is believed,
but by 1825 he had been denied the chair of landscape painting at the Dresd=
en academy=E2=80=94a sinecure he would have coveted. His style would subseq=
uently be eclipsed by that of the Dusseldorf Academy, which had a more dire=
ct influence on American landscape painting later in the century. Much of F=
riedrich=E2=80=99s work, which is now displayed in Germany or Russia, was f=
orgotten and had to be rediscovered at various times, for purposes it=E2=80=
=99s doubtful that Friedrich would have supported. All of which is to say
that the appeal of this kind of romanticism is recurring, but not long-live=
d. Or, maybe I should say, let=E2=80=99s hope it=E2=80=99s not long-lived t=
his time.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
